US government wants to restrict the reception of refugees
The US government wants to drastically restrict the reception of refugees. On Thursday, the US State Department declared that the annual upper limit of a resettlement program should be lowered from the current 30,000 to 18,000 refugees, which corresponds to an cut of 40 percent.
The State Department said that while the US remains committed to supporting refugees, the most important task is to protect and serve US citizens. Currently, the US immigration system is overburdened.
In the future, the US government wants to focus on taking in two groups of refugees: people who are persecuted for their faith - and Iraqis who have helped the US military in the country and are thus in danger, as the State Department's statement shows. However, a maximum of 1,500 refugees from Honduras, Guatemala and El Salvador are to be taken in.
Launched in 1980, the program selects refugees from UN camps around the world and resettles them in the U.S. The cap of 18,000 refugees for 2020 would be the lowest in the history of the program. Even the current ceiling of 30,000 is a low. When US President Donald Trump's predecessor, Barack Obama, left the White House, the number was nearly 85,000.
Aid organizations were horrified to the announced lowering of the ceiling. " This is a very sad day for America, " said David Miliband, head of the International Rescue Committee, and the US would further damage its leadership in protecting the world's most vulnerable people.
Trump is trying to strictly limit immigration to the US, both legally and illegally. According to the US government, he expects 350,000 asylum applications for the coming budget year. These figures are separate from the resettlement program.
Donald Trump - " Join a spy "
US President Donald Trump has accused whistleblowers of espionage in the whistleblower affair. Whoever has given information to the informant who accuses him of abuse of power " comes close to a spy, " Trump said according to a recording at a private event in New York on Thursday, as several US media agree.
When asked about the person who informed the whistleblower about controversial events in the White House, he replied, " That comes close to a spy. " Then Trump added, " Do you know what we did in ancient times when we were smart? Right. The spies and betrayal, we used to deal with it a bit differently than we do now. "
Observers considered the latter remark to be a possible allusion to the death penalty. The Democrats strongly criticised Trump's statements and accused him of intimidating witnesses. It was also an attempt to obstruct a Congressional investigation into a possible impement ment case against him, the leaders of the House House Affairs, Intelligence, and Oversight Committees.
In a recently published complaint, the whistleblower accuses the president of having abused his office to request another country to interference in the 2020 US election. Specifically, it concerns, among other things, his controversial telephone conversation with his Ukrainian counterpart Volodymyr Selensky in the summer: In the conversation, Trump advised him to launch an investigation against his possible democratic challenger Joe Biden and his son Hunter in Ukraine. Trump denies any misconduct.
It is still unclear who both the whistleblower himself and his informants are, but as the New York Times reports, the whistleblower is said to be a CIA analyst.
Refugee boat capsized: Baby and toddlers drown in the Aegean Sea
Again and again people try to get from Turkey to Greece via the Aegean Sea. The often too small boats regularly capsize. Seven migrants - including five children - have now been killed when a rubber dinghy sank.
Seven migrants were killed off the Greek island of Chios in the sinking of a rubber dinghy, including a baby and four other children, reported the Greek Coast Guard. Four children, three women and five men, were rescued from the floods by the crew of a passing ferry.
Among the victims is said to be a smuggler, reported the local news portal of Chios, Alithia.gr. The migrants had left Turkey in the morning. They had tried to reach the small archipelago of Inousses in the northeast of the island of Chios. Inousses is located between Chios and the Turkish mainland.
It is not yet known which countries the migrants come from. Currently, hundreds of migrants from Turkey transfer to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean, mostly in far too small boats. Last year, according to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), 174 people were killed on this route.
The Who cancel concert
A US concert by the rock band The Who has come to an abrupt end due to a disment by lead singer Roger Daltrey. In the middle of the performance on Wednesday evening (local time) in Houston, his voice failed to perform. At the eighth song, Daltrey told the audience: " I think I should leave it as long as it was still running. "
Lead guitarist Pete Townsend apologized and added that Daltrey " really could not speak now. " Townsend promised the audience to get his money's worth at a reparation concert. However, a date is not yet fixed.
Performances planned for Friday in Dallas and for Sunday in Denver cancelled The Who. They are to be made up at a later date. 75-year-old Daltrey and his 74-year-old bandmate Townsend are the only remaining founding members. The British cult band formed 55 years ago.
Rental suddenly stopped: WeWork makes real estate markets tremble
WeWork has become the largest office tenant in New York.
Within a few years, WeWork rises from a small startup to a driving force in the most expensive real estate markets in the world. But now the company is in crisis.
The crisis of the office landlord WeWork threatens to disturrupt the balance in the largest real estate markets in the world. A few days ago, the company had disposed founder Adam Neumann as CEO, postponed the planned IPO and started selling subsidiaries and assets such as the private jet for the executives in order to gain financial leeway for the coming weeks and months. In addition, the British " Financial Times, " among others reports that WeWork has stopped the conclusion of new rentals with immediate effect. Thus, the largest tenant of office space in New York and London, among others, is suddenly off the market.
WeWork rents large office space in the long term and rents it out to members at short notice in partly small units. These can be individual freelancers, small startups or entire departments of large corporations. So far, WeWork burns money with this business at a breathtaking speed. Last year, the company recorded a loss of 1.6 billion dollars, with a turnover of 1.8 billion dollars. This year alone, the rental costs are said to have risen to an estimated 2.5 billion dollars by renting ever new large space. In order to limit the loss, the new management is now said to have pulled the emergency brake and stopped the lease of new space with immediate effect.
According to the Financial Times, WeWork has now entered into leases with maturities of up to 15 years, resulting in liabilities of more than $40 billion. These huge liabilities could become a problem not only for the company itself and its investors, but for entire real estate markets.
According to calculations by the economist Dan Alpert of Cornell Law School in New York, WeWork has rented ased almost 300,000 square meters of office space in Manhattan, one of the most expensive real estate markets in the world, over the past 24 months. WeWorks new contracts alone ensured that the demand for offices in New York was greater than the space that newly came onto the market at the time. Without WeWorks expansion, the office vacancy in the US metropolis would have increased during this time, as Alpert wrote in the " Business Insider. " The situation is similar in London, where WeWork now operates several dozen office locations in a prime location.
In the British capital, too, the balance in the real estate market could be noticeably pushed without a further expansion of the aggressive startup. Among other things, WeWork is the main tenant, in an office building in the center of the financial metropolis bought last year by the Sparkassen fund provider Deka for almost 100 million euros.
Many landlords have converted their properties for the requirements of WeWork with high investments. If WeWork fails to make its business model profitable soon, the property owners would probably have to write off part of the hoped-for billions in revenues. They do not have access to the - scarce - reserves of WeWork despite the long-term lease contracts. The rental of the individual locations of WeWork is usually carried out by specially founded subsidiaries, so-called Special Purpose Vehicles, for which the parent company is only liable within tight limits.
Russia once again arrested numerous North Korean fishermen
The Russian Coast Guard has once again taken action against North Korean fishermen. In recent days, a total of another 262 poachers have been arrested who have fished illegally in the waters, the Russian domestic intelligence service FSB informed, according to the Interfax agency on Friday.
Only ten days ago, 161 fishermen from North Korea were arrested. Previously, the border guards had been shot at and three of them injured. This time, there had been no casualties, it was said. Communist North Korea is suffering from chronic food shortages.
The North Korean fishermen were therefore on their way in Russian territorial waters. There, according to its own information, the Russian Coast Guard drives patrols to protect their marine biological resources. 30,000 squid were discovered during the new inspections. According to the data, three fishing and two motor boats were confiscated and brought to Nakodka and Posjet near Vladivostok. According to the Ria Novostostagency, the Coast Guard found a total of more than 8,000 violations in 2018.
Even after complaints by local entrepreneurs, the Russian Fisheries Authority had not issued any fishing licenses to the North Koreans this year. According to the media, thousands of fishermen from North Korea were already temporarily arrested there in 2019.
The head of the Association of Russian Fisheries Companies in the Far Eastern Region of Primorsky Krai, Georgi Martynov, recently complained of high ecological damage caused by North Korean fishermen. They fished with close-meshed synthetic nets banned in Russia. These would also bring small creatures from the sea. In addition, the nets would simply be disposed of in the sea, where they would take 200 years to be decomposed. Also, the ships themselves would not comply with hygienic and technical regulations.
According to Moscow, three members of the Russian Coast Guard were injured in the arrests last week. According to the FSB, a wounded North Korean man also died later of his injuries. On September 17, Russian border guards first detained a North Korean boat and then a second after it had opened fire.
US imposes entry ban on former President Castro
The US has imposed entry bans on former Cuban President Raúl Castro and his children, as the US State Department justified in a statement on Thursday with Castro's involvement in " gross human rights violations. " As head of the Caribbean Communist Party, he presides over a system in which thousands of Cubans are arbitrarily arrested and there are more than 100 political prisoners.
As chairman of the armed forces, the brother of the late revolutionary leader Fidel Castro is also complicit in human rights violations there by supporting the President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro. " The disregard for human rights and the use of force by the Cuban regime to support the former Maduro regime are responsible for the ongoing crises in Cuba and Venezuela, " American Secretary of State Mike Pompeo tweeted.
President Donald Trump issued entry bans on members of the Venezuelan government and military, among others, on Wednesday. A fierce power struggle between the government and the opposition has been raging in Venezuela for months. The US has imposed a series of sanctions on Maduro's government in order to bring him to his knees and help the opposition leader and self-proclaimed interim president Juan Guaidó to power.
Cuba is considered one of Maduro's closest allies. The socialist Caribbean island receives oil from Venezuela in exchange for the services of posted doctors. According to the US and the Venezuelan opposition, Cuba has also sent numerous intelligence agents to Venezuela to help the government suppress opponents of the government.
New Fridays for Future protests
One week after the biggest international climate protests to date, thousands and thousands of people want to take to the streets for more climate protection.
At the end of an international climate strike week, the Fridays for Future movement is once again planning actions and rallies in dozens of countries around the world. Because of the time difference New Zealand and Australia Australia are likely to start before the protests spread across Europe to North America. There, climate activist Greta Thunberg wanted to participate in a large-scale rally in Montreal, Canada. Demonstrators also wanted to gather in front of the White House in Washington.
How great the worldwide popularity will be this Friday after the record participation of last week is relatively unclear. Thunberg herself was in good spirits. " Last Friday, more than four million people went on strike for the climate. We'll do it again this Friday! " she wrote on Twitter. So far, there have been 6,383 actions in 170 countries as part of the strike week, she added.
The influx of last Friday was particularly high in Germany. According to estimates by Fridays for Future, a good third of all demonstrators worldwide - around 1.4 million - took part in the protests in 575 German cities. This time, according to the movement, rallies are planned in at least 65 cities. Among them in metropolises such as Berlin, Hamburg, Munich and Cologne, but also in smaller communities and cities such as Jüchen in North Rhine-Westphalia or Westerland on Sylt, people want to take to the streets for the climate.
At the age of 15, Thunberg sat down in front of the Swedish Parliament in August 2018 to call on their country's politicians to step up their commitment to climate protection, which led to the emerging Fridays for Future movement within a short time. Pupils and students are taking part in the climate protests, but increasingly also scientists and other adults.
Together, they demand more ambition from politicians in the fight against earth heating and the impending climate catastrophe. Above all, according to the Paris climate agreement, global warming must be reduced to below 1.5 degrees compared to pre-industrial times.
Almost a month ago, after a two-week transatlantic cruise, Thunberg arrived in New York on a deep-sea racing yacht, where she recently participated in United Nations climate protests and summits. On Monday, she gave an emotional spespeech at the UN in which she spoke to the conscience of the world's heads of state and government. In her home country of Stockholm, she was awarded the Alternative Nobel Prize of the Right Livelihood Foundation on Wednesday for her commitment to more climate protection.
Russia forbids smoking on the balcony
People in Russia will no longer be allowed to smoke on the balcony, which provides for a change in fire protection. " This also applies to smoking, " said a spokesman for the Ministry of Emergency, according to the Tass agency in Moscow on Thursday. The ban is due to enter into force on 1 October.
Anyone who smokes nevertheless must therefore expect a fine of 3,000 rubles (42.46 euros). If the cigarette should light a fire, then the penalty will be higher. According to the ministry, the ban also includes burning candles. Also grilling meat skewers on the balcony is no longer allowed.
Strike cybercriminals - investigators dig servers
In the fight against crime on the Internet, German investigators have for the first time dug out a large server provider for illegal business on the darknet.
A total of 13 perpetrators are suspected of having hosted numerous websites as the operator of a data center in a former NATO bunker in Traben-Trarbach on the Moselle, through which internationally active criminals carried out their machinations.
This was announced by the Prosecutor General's Office in Koblenz. Seven suspects were arrested on Thursday evening in a large-scale action. Darknet is a shielded part of the Internet.
Customers of the suspects are said to have been the operators of the world's second largest darknet marketplace for drugs, " Wall Street Market, " which was smashed by investigators in the spring. According to the Attorney General's Office, the attack on 1.25 million telecom routers at the end of November 2016 was also controlled via a server in the cyberbunker.
Such a hoster was excavated for the first time in Germany, it was said. A web host provides the infrastructure for a website.
During the access campaign with the support of special units such as the GSG9, there were searches in Germany and neighbouring countries. It was the result of almost five years of investigation. At noon, the investigators want to inform about further details.
