An actor and Youtuber adds Egypt's ruler: For the time being, however, Mohamed Ali prefers to stay abroad.
The two men who have an influence on whether blood flows again on the streets of Egypt both spent last week abroad. One of them was returned to Cairo airport on Friday. President Abdelfattah al-Sisi returned from the UN General Assembly. The ex-general who deposed the Muslim Brotherhood Mohamed Morsi, the country's first freely elected head of state, had spent a pleasant time in New York: US President Donald Trump had praised Sisi's actions against political Islam and had lost no syllable about the human rights violations on the Nile - in a week in which Egypt's security forces arrested hundreds of people for daring to protest against the president. He had " no reason to worry, " Sisi said at the airport in the microphones of the state television. " The Egyptians will not be misled. "
According to the president, the other man who is currently determining events on the streets is trying to mislead this. Mohamed Ali, of course, remained abroad, where he escapes the grip of the security forces, who would immediately arrest him if he tried to set foot on Egyptian soil. Weeks ago, the 45-year-old was known as an actor to only a minority of Egyptians. Today, he is the leading voice that dominates the political discourse in the country's cafés, living rooms and tea rooms: with his YouTube channel, " Mohammed's Secrets, " Ali calls on his compatriots to rise up against Sisi.
He approaches the head of state directly and in quite rustic language. While the people are starving, the president is indulging in luxury and has magnificent new palaces built for him, it is said. Ali reaccuses the army leadership on which Sisi bases his rule of corruption and enrichment. Because he did business with these very gentlemen for 15 years in his second job as a building contractor, he seems to know pretty well what he is talking about - at least that is the impression of many Egyptians, as the almost exploding click numbers show.
After thousands of people had demonstrated against his rule for the first time since Sisi's grip on power and almost 2,000 citizens, among them prominent civil society figures, human rights lawyers and opposition politicians, had been arrested, Ali called for a " march of millions " for this Friday. It was unlikely that so many people would really venture into the streets. However, there were isolated smaller protests, for example in Giza near Cairo and in the village of Kina near Luxor. Videos on social media showed protests, whose participants accused Al-Sisi of causing corruption and demanded his departure. In these protests, the police also used tear gas and rubber bullets. These videos could not be verified at first. It was said from security circles that the police had ended the protests.
