Aegean Sea: Baby and four other children drown in case of boat accident
One baby and four other children drowned while capsizing in the Aegean Sea. In total, seven people died in the accident, as the Greek Coast Guard announced on Friday. Nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men were rescued.
Hundreds of migrants from Turkey are currently moving to the Greek islands in the eastern Aegean Sea. According to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), 174 people died on this route last year. Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer has now announced his intention to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the responsible EU Commissioner, he wanted to " find out what the refugee situation is like in Turkey, " said Seehofer on Friday. Afterwards, he wanted to learn more about the " administrative problems of the Greeks " in Athens in order to be able to help cope with them.
A spokesperson for the EU Commission confirmed Seehofer's planned trip on Friday with EU Interior Commissioner Dimitris Avramopoulos and French Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
Unusually large numbers of migrants from Turkey continue to arrive in Greece. On Tuesday alone, 654 people moved to the Greek islands, said the Greek Ministry of Civil Protection on Wednesday.
Does the Turkey deal still work?
The increase in have recently raised doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey agreement concluded in 2016. This provides that the EU can send back all refugees and migrants who come to the Greek islands illegally via Turkey. In return, the EU wanted to take in a Syrian refugee from Turkey for every deported Syrian.
However, due to a shortage of personnel, the processing of asylum applications is difficult on the Greek side. According to the Ministry of Civil Protection, almost 29,400 people are waiting for Lesbos, Chios, Samos, Leros and Kos. The situation on Lesbos is the worst: 5,200 migrants are currently housed in a camp with capacities for 650 people.
Never before since the entry into force of the EU-Turkey Refugee Pact in March 2016 have there been so many, reported the state broadcaster.
Climate change: heat causes more heart attacks
According to physicians, climate change will put the health system to the test in the future. Climate change is " certainly " one of the biggest challenges for the health system in the next 20 to 50 years, said Andreas Zeiher, President of the German Society of Cardiology. High temperatures and large temperature jumps in particular have caused problems for the cardiovascular system within a short period of time and increasingly led to heart attacks. People with cardiovascular diseases, the elderly and diabetics in particular are affected.
Green politician has to answer for embarrassing photo breakdown
The head of the Canadian Greens, Elizabeth May, in the election campaign - was the mug manipulated for this reason?
The Canadian Green leader holds a reusable cup in her hand in a photo. But now it came out: The cup was manipulated.
Ottawa / Canada - It has gone unnoticed for quite a long time - and finally noticed. Elizabeth May, the head of the Canadian Greens, never held the reusable coffee cup with metal straw in her hand. On the party's website, she was seen on a photo with this cup, in conversation with citizens. However, the photo had already been published and also distributed to the media - and the cup was still a disdainful (cardboard) cup, as the Canadian National Post reported.
Head of the Green Party must answer for photo breakdown
The National Post then accused May of manipulation and producing fake news to appear more credible credible on the subject of " environmental protection, " in the middle of a campaign for the House of Commons, in which Trudeau is increasingly struggling with a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral on social media and sparked the discussion about fake news. A user shares a juxtaposition of the photos and writes: " The Greens manipulate a photo of their chairmen to hide their disposable cup. "
May was shocked and asserted on her blog that she had not known about this action. To underline this, she immediately posted the original: She, in conversation with citizens, put a cup in her hand. However, however, she corrected correctly, was made of bamboo. She always had it with her. A spokeswoman for the party said that it was only about placing the party logo in the picture and not about covering something up. Only an excerpt of the photo can be seen on the website.
May writes that she is sorry for the employee who did that. " I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide, " she told the Guardian and at the same time asked for something from her over-committed team: " If they feel like working on a picture again, couldn't they do something with my face so that I look younger? "
