Influencer wants free upgrade: Cathay lifelong flight ban
Jaqueline Ng was allegedly promised an upgrade by mail from Cathay Pacific. However, when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed on board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Getting a Business Class upgrade spontaneously - many passengers dream of that. Sometimes they are lucky, and the check-in staff offer a change from Economy Class for free.
However, this case shows how not to do it: a self-proclaimed influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. Jaqueline Ng follows more than 65,000 users on Instagram. On May 30, she flew back from Taiwan to New York and on June 7.
On the outward flight, employees refused to upgrade Jaqueline, even though she had presented an e-mail in which Cathay Pacific allegedly promised her an upgrade. The influencer claims to have received the letter from a marketing employee of the airline. The airline, however, accuses Jaqueline of forging the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have shown the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK airport were sceptical: They checked the headquarters. And, indeed, the employee from whom the mail allegedly originated is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system in which the messages did not appear.
The airline staff at the airport cancelled Jaqueline's ticket and imposed a lifelong flight ban with Cathay Pacific. She had to buy a new ticket to Taiwan for 1,400 US dollars (around 1,280 euros).
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests. Cathay had reimbursed her for the price of her original ticket, but Jaqueline also demanded the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: the influencer has committed fraud for Cathay, she remains closed for future flights. Furthermore, the airline's terms and conditions state that she does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline does not want to be satisfied with this - and now hires a lawyer.
Oil prices fall after ceasefire report in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar within a very short time on Friday afternoon. Most recently, a barrel (159 liters) of Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - about 1.4 percent less than the day before. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
The slide was triggered by a Wall Street Journal report on a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on the oil facilities in Saudi Arabia had brought five percent of global oil production to a standstill in mid-September. Houthi rebels in the civil war country of Yemen, allied with Iran, had claimed the attacks. Saudi Arabia, like the US government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse the political tension in the region.
If an agreement is actually reached, one could focus on growth and demand concerns, said Ole Hansen, Head of Commodity Strategy at Saxo Bank of the Bloomberg news agency.
Oil prices thus continue its downward movement of the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had cost up to almost $59, Brent almost $65.
Most recently, Bloomberg, citing insiders, reported that repair work on oil plants in Saudi Arabia is progressing faster than expected after the mid-September attack. Accordingly, production volume has again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original volume.
Most recently, there have been several press releases citing insiders who report on rapid progress made by the state-owned oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some détente in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: the British oil tanker " Stena Impero " is on its way to leave the port more than two months after the arrest by Iran and the recently granted release. Now, the crew is preparing for departure while the ship is still at anchor, shipping company boss Erik Hånell told the Swedish radio in a text message on Friday morning.
However, the US announced that it would transfer defensive missiles and soldiers to the Iranian arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fear of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and the UK had temporarily driven up oil prices in recent weeks.
