North Korea considers third summit of Trump and Kim questionable
North Korea has raised doubts that the nuclear dispute will soon see a third summit of rulers Kim Jong-un and US President Donald Trump. The meaning and prospects of success of such a meeting are questionable due to the lack of progress in implementing agreements at the first summit in Singapore, top diplomat Kim Kye-gwan said on Friday, according to the agency KCNA.
The US has so far done nothing to implement the summit's decisions last year, said the adviser to the North Korean State Department. He also criticized US sanctions and the joint military manoeuvres of the US and South Korea. However, he hoped that Trump would make " wise " and " courageous " decision to return to rapprochement.
Trump said on Monday that he wanted to know what a third summit with Kim should bring before he agrees to do so. Negotiations on disarm the North Korea's nuclear and missile program have stalled since the failed second summit of Trump and Kim in Hanoi in February. In June, both met in the demilitarized zone between the two Korean states. They agreed to revive the talks, but so far without much success.
